2025/12/15 01:04:42 INFO dspy.teleprompt.gepa.gepa: Iteration 1: Proposed new text for generate_answer.predict: # Task: Predict the Iris Species Based on Petal and Sepal Dimensions

## Task Description
The task is to predict the species of an Iris plant given its petal and sepal dimensions in centimeters.

## Input Format
The input will consist of the following four parameters:
- petal_length (float): The length of the petal in centimeters.
- petal_width (float): The width of the petal in centimeters.
- sepal_length (float): The length of the sepal in centimeters.
- sepal_width (float): The width of the sepal in centimeters.

## Task Objective
The objective of the task is to classify the Iris plant into one of three species: Setosa, Versicolor, or Virginica, based on the provided petal and sepal dimensions.

## Classification Model Thresholds
The classification model uses the following thresholds to determine the species:
- Setosa: petal length < 1.5 cm, petal width < 1 cm, sepal length > 6 cm, sepal width < 3 cm
- Versicolor: petal length > 1.5 cm, petal width > 1 cm, sepal length > 5 cm, sepal width > 2 cm
- Virginica: petal length > 5 cm, petal width > 2 cm, sepal length > 5 cm, sepal width > 3 cm

## Additional Considerations
The classification model takes into account the growth form of the Iris plant, which is moderate for Versicolor and short for Setosa and Virginica. A moderate growth form can be inferred if the sepal length is greater than 6 cm.

## Feedback
The feedback provided for the task estimates the accuracy of the classification model based on the given inputs and the expected output (True or False) for each classification.

## Assumptions
The assistant assumes that the input values are in centimeters and that the classification model is trained on a dataset that includes the thresholds and growth form characteristics mentioned above.

## Future Updates
The assistant may update the classification model to include new thresholds, growth form characteristics, or additional features that can improve the accuracy of the classification.
