2025/12/15 01:05:15 INFO dspy.teleprompt.gepa.gepa: Iteration 4: Proposed new text for generate_answer.predict: # Task: Predict the Iris Species Based on Petal and Sepal Dimensions

## Task Description
The task is to predict the species of an Iris plant given its petal and sepal dimensions in centimeters. The task involves classifying the Iris plant into one of three species: Setosa, Versicolor, or Virginica, based on the provided petal and sepal dimensions.

## Input Format
The input will consist of the following four parameters:
- petal_length (float): The length of the petal in centimeters.
- petal_width (float): The width of the petal in centimeters.
- sepal_length (float): The length of the sepal in centimeters.
- sepal_width (float): The width of the sepal in centimeters.

## Task Objective
The objective of the task is to classify the Iris plant into one of three species: Setosa, Versicolor, or Virginica, based on the provided petal and sepal dimensions.

## Classification Model Thresholds
The classification model uses the following thresholds to determine the species:
- Setosa: petal length < 1.5 cm, petal width < 1 cm, sepal length > 6 cm, sepal width < 3 cm
- Versicolor: petal length > 1.5 cm, petal width > 1 cm, sepal length > 5 cm, sepal width > 2 cm
- Virginica: petal length > 5 cm, petal width > 2 cm, sepal length > 5 cm, sepal width > 3 cm

## Additional Considerations
The classification model takes into account the growth form of the Iris plant, which is moderate for Versicolor and short for Setosa and Virginica. A moderate growth form can be inferred if the sepal length is greater than 6 cm.

## Feedback
The feedback provided for the task estimates the accuracy of the classification model based on the given inputs and the expected output (True or False) for each classification.

## Assumptions
The assistant assumes that the input values are in centimeters and that the classification model is trained on a dataset that includes the thresholds and growth form characteristics mentioned above.

## Future Updates
The assistant may update the classification model to include new thresholds, growth form characteristics, or additional features that can improve the accuracy of the classification.

## Domain-Specific Information
- Iris plants have three main species: Setosa, Versicolor, and Virginica.
- Setosa plants typically have short stems and leaves.
- Versicolor plants typically have moderate growth forms and can be confused with Virginica plants.
- Virginica plants typically have tall stems and leaves.
- A moderate growth form can be inferred if the sepal length is greater than 6 cm.
- The classification model uses the following thresholds to determine the species:
  - Setosa: petal length < 1.5 cm, petal width < 1 cm, sepal length > 6 cm, sepal width < 3 cm
  - Versicolor: petal length > 1.5 cm, petal width > 1 cm, sepal length > 5 cm, sepal width > 2 cm
  - Virginica: petal length > 5 cm, petal width > 2 cm, sepal length > 5 cm, sepal width > 3 cm

## Strategy
If the sepal length is greater than 6 cm, the classification model assumes a moderate growth form and infers the species as Versicolor if the petal length and width are greater than the thresholds, otherwise it infers the species as Setosa if the petal length and width are less than the thresholds.

## Assumptions for Future Updates
Any future updates to the classification model should include the following considerations:
- New thresholds for petal and sepal dimensions
- New growth form characteristics
- Additional features that can improve the accuracy of the classification

## Note
The assistant should update the classification model based on new information and new thresholds, growth form characteristics, or additional features that can improve the accuracy of the classification.
